PARAGRAPH.#text: (Updates with additional information from FDA starting in first paragraph) WASHINGTON (Dow Jones)--The Food and Drug Administration said Friday it was increasing regulation of companies making widely used infusion pumps that deliver drugs and other fluids to patients, a move that follows continued reports of problems with the devices. These pumps are used in the hospital to deliver IV antibiotics, chemotherapy to cancer patients and anesthesia to patients undergoing surgery. The pumps also increasingly are being used in the home-setting to deliver medication, including insulin, to patients.

The agency didn't immediately release details of the proposed requirements but said it would release draft guidelines later Friday.
